post_text:
Update on Spring Sport Season

March 16, 2020

The MIAA Board of Directors voted today, March 16, 2020, to amend the start of the 2020 spring sports season in light of recent mandates from Governor Baker and recommendations from governing health agencies. The updated start date for the 2020 spring season is April 27, 2020.

Additionally, the MIAA Board of Directors voted to have completion of regular season and tournament games by June 20, 2020 with consideration of June 21, 2020 for weather and facility needs.

Details regarding the structure of the spring season will be addressed by the Tournament Management Committee (TMC). An update will be provided and reviewed by the Board by March 25, 2020.

These decisions are based on available information and are made in the best interest of our student-athletes, schools and communities. These decisions will be revisited and adjusted as needed.

Thank you for your patience while dealing with this very fluid situation. Be well.

Schools Closed until April 7 per Governor Baker.....

Gov. Baker ordered a slate of other coronavirus changes, including:

No on-premise consumption at restaurants or bars; takeout or delivery only, effective Tuesday

Gatherings of over 25 people will be prohibited, including all community, civic, public, leisure, faith-based events, sporting events with spectators, concerts, conventions, and any similar event or activity

Requirements will be relaxed around unemployment claims

Visitation will be restricted at long-term care facilities and nursing homes

Hospitals will postpone elective surgeries

Commercial health insurance carriers will deliver services via Telehealth

shared_text:
North Attleboro Police Department
August 26, 2019 at 9:27 AM ·

With school starting in North Attleboro next week we wanted to send out a reminder about the rules for stopping for school busses.
Failing to stop or illegally passing a stopped school bus with flashing lights can result in a $250 fine in Massachusetts, at minimum. A second offense by a fine of not less than $500. That fine can go up to $2,000 and a suspended license of up to a year for subsequent offenses (MGL 90-14).
Please stop for school bus stop signs- it’s the law and it will save lives. Thank you!

This is a good article to help explain:
https://www.google.com/amp/s/patch.com/massachusetts/arlington/amp/27245330/death-zone-what-know-passing-stopped-school-bus-massachusetts

Congratulations to our HS and MS students accepted into SEMMA Junior District Festival.

The teachers "are so proud of the hard work they put into learning their music to be able to perform at the concert today".

They also wanted to celebrate Middle School student Matthew Garofalo who was selected out of around 70 students from a choir of about 200 students to perform a solo at today's performance!

Here are the student's names from left to right.

Back Row: Sharon Jabbour (High School), Haley Brodbeck (H.S.), Ryan Gula (H.S.), Anna Pusateri(H.S.),Lucas Manso( Middle School), Nicole Donato (M.S.), Branigan Smith (M.S.), Nathanial Burns (M.S.)

Front Row: Julia Curran (H.S.), Samantha Willey (H.S.), Kathleen Barrett (H.S.), Gianna Solbo (M.S.), Sofia Bertino (M.S.), Matthew Garofalo (M.S.), Kori Sheaff (M.S.)

post_text:
A message sent to families this afternoon...

Good afternoon, this is Assistant Superintendent Lori McEwen with a message regarding student safety.

I have been in contact with the NAPD regarding some recent incidents in which a man in his 50s, with a gray or white beard and hair, asked a child if he needed a ride home.

The man is reported to be driving a blue or gray truck or van, and the license may contain the numbers 32. Police in Wrentham have received similar reports, according to NAPD and an article in the Sun Chronicle.

As a result, the NAPD is posting police officers at all elementary schools this afternoon. In addition, school staff are reiterating safe walking procedures with students.

Please stress walking safety with your children and report any suspicious activity to the police at 508-695-1212.

As always, your children's safety is our primary concern.

Thank you.

post_text:
Give and it will be given to you.

What a wonderful meeting with Mr. James Flanagan and his daughter, Ms. Linda Sheme. Mr. Flanagan came up from Florida to present the North Attleborough School Department with a $25,000 check to establish a scholarship for North Attleborough High School graduates who are going to major in the field of technology/electronics. For the next five years, 2 graduates will each receive a check for $2,500.

This scholarship is being established in the name of Mr. Flanagan’s late wife, Ms. Nola Priestley Flanagan. Ms. Nola Priestly Flanagan was a 1946 graduate of North Attleborough High School and worked as the Administrative Assistant to North Attleborough Superintendent, Mr. Mott. Ms. Flanagan passed away this past June and wanted to give back to the community she loved and always held near and dear to her heart.

We thank the family for their generosity and look forward to giving the scholarship out for years to come.

God Bless….

On behalf of everyone at North Bowl I would like thank Scott Holcomb and the North Attleboro School District for giving us the opportunity to bring "In School Bowling" to all five of North Attleboro's Elementary Schools. The kick off was at Martin School today and it was very exciting to see all the kids having a great time bowling. When they finish the program we look forward to bringing the kids to North Bowl for a field trip where they can try out their new skills on our lanes.

On behalf of everyone at North Bowl I would like thank Scott Holcomb and the North Attleboro School District for giving us the opportunity to bring "In School Bowling" to all five of North Attleboro's Elementary Schools. post_text: Visiting Veteran and currently serving in San Antonio Texas, Lt Colonel Antoinette Burns is a doctor in the military. She emphasized continued education and provided "doctor tools" for the students to examine from her doctor's travel bag. Grade 5 students in Ms. Johnson's class, Mr. Kummer's class, Ms. Silva's class, along with Grade 1 students in Ms. Crear's class were able to ask questions of Lt. Colonel Burns which included her military service, her educational achievements, and her world travel. She has traveled to Germany, South Korea and multiple states in the USA serving military families needing medical care. Lt. Colonel Burns commented on how polite and respectful the Community Elementary School students were and she enjoyed their thoughtful questions.

post_text:
A few changes to the school calendar were approved at last night’s school committee meeting. Elementary Open Houses were scheduled for the following dates:

September 7 – Falls Elementary School

September 12 – Amvet Boulevard School

September 19 – Community School

September 26 – Martin School K-2

September 27 – Martin School 3-5

September 27 – Roosevelt Avenue School

To accommodate the elementary open houses, conferences will be held DAY ONLY on March 28.

The High School Open House has been moved to September 28.
